ague|2008\u201309]]\n|A-League\n|10||0||1||0||3||0||14||0\n|<ref name=\"wf\"/>\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!20!!4!!1!!0!!3!!0!!24!!4\n!\u2013\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!412!!113!!18!!9!!15!!3!!445!!125\n!\u2013\n|}\n<sup>1</sup> \u2013 included [[A-League]] final series statistics<br/>\n<sup>2</sup> \u2013 includes [[FIFA Club World Cup|Club World Cup]] statistics; [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] statistics; [[UEFA Intertoto Cup]] statistics; [[AFC Champions League|Asian Champions League]] statistics (included in season commencing after group stages).\n\n===International===\n:Source:<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\"|[[Australia national soccer team|Australia]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|1996||2||0\n|-\n|2000||12||5\n|-\n|2001||2||0\n|-\n|2004||1||1\n|-\n|2005||1||0\n|-\n!Total||18||6\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n:Source:<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n:''Scores and results list Australia's goal tally first.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! No !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 15 February 2000 || [[Estadio Playa Ancha]], [[Valpara\u00edso]], [[Chile]] || {{fb|BUL}} || 1\u20130 || 1\u20131 || [[Exhibition game|Friendly]]\n|-\n| 2. || 29 June 2000 || [[Papeete]], [[Tahiti]] || {{fb|Cook Islands}} || 1\u20130 || 17\u20130 || [[2000 OFC Nations Cup|OFC Nations Cup 2000]]\n|-\n| 3. || 29 June 2000 || Papeete, Tahiti || {{fb|Cook Islands}} || 12\u20130 || 17\u20130 || OFC Nations Cup 2000\n|-\n| 4. || 7 October 2000 || [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]] || {{fb|KOR}} || 1\u20130 || 2\u20134 || Friendly\n|-\n| 5. || 7 October 2000 || Dubai, United Arab Emirates || {{fb|KOR}} || 2\u20130 || 2\u20134 || Friendly\n|-\n| 6. || 18 February 2004 || [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico (Caracas)|Estadio Ol\u00edmpico]], [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]] || {{fb|VEN}} || 1\u20130 || 1\u20131 || Friendly\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Country===\n'''Australia'''\n* [[OFC Nations Cup]]: [[2000 OFC Nations Cup|2000]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Fussballdaten|agostinopaul|Paul Agostino}}\n* [http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/Players/A/AG.html#AgostinoPaul OzFootball profile]\n\n{{Australia men's football squad 1996 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Australia squad 2000 OFC Nations Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Agostino, Paul}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Australian soccer players]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate soccer players]]\n[[Category:Australia international soccer players]]\n[[Category:Olympic soccer players of Australia]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:A-League players]]\n[[Category:National Soccer League (Australia) players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:2. Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Swiss Super League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Salisbury United FC players]]\n[[Category:Adelaide United FC players]]\n[[Category:BSC Young Boys players]]\n[[Category:West Adelaide SC players]]\n[[Category:TSV 1860 Munich players]]\n[[Category:Yverdon Sport FC players]]\n[[Category:Bristol City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate sportspeople in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate sportspeople in Germany]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Germany]]\n[[Category:Marquee players (A-League)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Paul Agostino\n| fullname       =\n| image          = Paul Agostino.jpg\n| caption        = Agostino\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1975|6|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Adelaide]], Australia\n| height         = 1.84 m\n| position       = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n| youthyears1    =\n| youthclubs1    = [[Salisbury United]]\n| years1         = 1990\n| clubs1         = [[Salisbury United]]\n| caps1          = \n| goals1         = \n| years2         = 1991\n| clubs2         = [[West Adelaide SC|West Adelaide]]\n| caps2          = 17\n| goals2         = 6\n| years3         = 1992\u20131994\n| clubs3         = [[BSC Young Boys|Young Boys]]\n| caps3          = 29\n| goals3         = 3\n| years4         = 1994\u20131995\n| clubs4         = [[Yverdon-Sport FC|Yverdon-Sport]]\n| caps4          = 9\n| goals4         = 3\n| years5         = 1995\u20131997\n| clubs5         = [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]\n| caps5          = 85\n| goals5         = 19\n| years6         = 1997\u20132007\n| clubs6         = [[TSV 1860 Munich|1860 Munich]]\n| caps6          = 248\n| goals6         = 77\n| years7         = 2006\n| clubs7         = [[TSV 1860 Munich II|1860 Munich II]]\n| caps7          = 4\n| goals7         = 1\n| years8         = 2007\u20132009\n| clubs8         = [[Adelaide United FC|Adelaide United]]\n| caps8          = 20\n| goals8         = 4\n| totalcaps      = 412\n| totalgoals     = 113\n| nationalyears1 = 1991\n| nationalteam1  = [[Australia national under-17 football team|Australia U-17]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 4\n| nationalgoals1 = 4\n| nationalyears2 = 1993\n| nationalteam2  = [[Australia national under-20 football team|Australia U-20]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 6\n| nationalgoals2 = 2\n| nationalyears3 = 1996\n| nationalteam3  = [[Australia national under-23 football team|Australia U-23]]\n| nationalcaps3  = 3\n| nationalgoals3 = 1\n| nationalyears4 = 1996\u20132005\n| nationalteam4  = [[Australia national association football team|Australia]]\n| nationalcaps4  = 18\n| nationalgoals4 = 7\n}}\n'''Paul Agostino''' (born 9 June 1975) is a Australian former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|striker]]. He played the majority of his club football outside Australia, most notably with [[TSV 1860 Munich|1860 Munich]] in Germany for ten years. He played 18 times for Australia, winning the [[OFC Nations Cup]] of the year 2000.\n\nAgostino attended Findon High School in his hometown of [[Adelaide]]. In 2011, he returned to Munich, where his wife Monika was born, with a view to settle there permanently. There he has since partnered with his former 1860 teammate [[Roman T\u00fdce]] and opened a soccer school called MunichSoccerCamp.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.dieblaue24.com/2011/08/25/maurer-wird-nur-ein-groser-1860-trainer-wenn-er-aufsteigt/ | title = <nowiki>\u201cMaurer wird nur ein gro\u00dfer 1860-Trainer, wenn er aufsteigt\u201d</nowiki> | language = German | publisher = dieblaue24.de | date = 25 August 2011 | accessdate = 10 January 2013 | first = Oliver | last = Griss}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.munichsoccercamp.de/ | title = msc | language = German | publisher = munichsoccercamp.de | accessdate = 9 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Adelaide]], Australia, Agostino started his club career at [[Salisbury United]]. He on to the national scene in 1991 in his first season at senior level with [[West Adelaide SC]] in the [[National Soccer League|NSL]]. It was at this time that \"Aga\" was picked in the Australian World Youth Championships squad \u2013 a squad which contained the likes of [[Paul Okon]] and [[Mark Bosnich]] during one of Australia's 'Golden Generations' \u2013 which made the semi-finals of that competition.\n\n===Overseas===\nAgostino left for Europe in 1992 and headed for Switzerland, where he signed with [[BSC Young Boys|Young Boys]]. Agostino stayed in [[Bern]] for two seasons which was invaluable in enabling him to adapt to European life and football. It was in Switzerland that he learnt to speak German which would later help his move to Germany in 1997. He then had a short stint with Yverdon before making the move to England. Agostino signed with [[Bristol City]] in 1995 and it was in his second season with Bristol City that he began to score more regularly, bagging 16 goals in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] (the third tier of English club football).\n\nAfter two productive seasons in [[Bristol]], Agostino's growing reputation caught the eye of German [[Bundesliga]] side 1860 Munich. He was signed by the club in 1997 at the age of 22. Agostino stayed with the [[Munich]] club for a full decade, enduring spells both in and out of the side. Agostino played at the highest level while in Munich, representing 1860 in both the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] and the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]. He enjoyed his best form for 1860 in the 2000\u201301 season, scoring 12 goals for the light blues, while Agostino regularly featured in the first team from 1999 to 2002. He fell down the pecking order at 1860 after this and typically played only a handful of games each season until it was revealed that he would be leaving the club on amicable terms at the end of the [[2006\u201307 2. Bundesliga]] season.\n\n===Adelaide United===\nIt was announced in February 2007 that [[A-League]] team [[Adelaide United FC|Adelaide United]] had agreed on a two-year contract with Agostino which saw the striker return to his home city for the first time in 15 years. It was announced on 30 December 2008 that Agostino would retire at the end of the 2008\u201309 season.\n\n==International career==\nAgostino debuted in 1996 in a match against Chile for the \"[[Australia national association football team|Socceroos]],\" the Australian national team. In 2005, he played versus South Africa for the 18th and last time for his country. In his 18 full international matches he scored seven goals. In 1999, he also played twice against the Brazilian \"B\" team, scoring two goals. In 1996, he was part of the Australian squad for the Olympics in Atlanta, but he was not used in Australia's three matches there.\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!c